    //         title: "Do you get interest from inactive EPF ACCOUNTS?",
    //         content: "<div class='blog-content'><p>Barring a minority of people, most of the salaried class treat their <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>EPF account</a> indifferently. The reason for this was the bureaucratic hassles that revolved around its transfer and withdrawal. The rules have however changed over the years, and the <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>EPFO</a> (employee provident fund organization) has made it easy to transfer accounts from one employer to the other, under the <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>UAN</a> (<a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>Universal Account Number</a>) option.</p><p>In order to reign in the employees who neglected their <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>EPF accoun</a>t as there no contribution being made, the <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>EPFO</a> decided to pass a law which stopped paying interest to <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>EPF account</a>s if no contribution was made for a period of 3 years. After three years the account was deemed to be inactive and no interest was forthcoming subsequently. This rule came into effect in the financial year 2011 – 2012. However in the year month of April 2016 this decision was reversed. Now even accounts that are dormant for over thirty six months or three years would continue getting interest. The interest payable was set to 8.8%. The terms and conditions that were set are the employee could withdraw the EPF after three months, only if had quit his job and had not taken on another job with an employer who provided EPF in this duration. The <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>EPF accoun</a>t is treated as dormant after three years and on interest will be due, after the retirement of the employee or if they have settled in a foreign country. In case the <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>EPF account</a> holder is no more; the account will become inactive. </p><p>Salaried individuals generally contribute 12 % of their salary on a monthly basis towards EPF, at 8.8% interest this works out to a substantial amount (depending on the individual’s salary). The advantage is that after five years the interest that is generated is free from tax. You also get benefit under section 80C of the income tax act if you contribute money to your <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>EPF account</a> up to rupees one lakh fifty thousand annually. </p><p>Salaried individuals can benefit from this new rule, if they move towards opening up their own business venture. The money lying in their <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>EPF account</a> will continue to garner interest till the retirement age as mentioned above.</p><p>Now that the EPF is providing interest at 8.8% annually and this interest is tax free, we urge you to start investing in this instrument as it also very safe and can help you build a substantial corpus over the years.</p></div>",
