    //         title: "Steps to avoid investment mistakes",
    //         content: "<div class='blog-content'><p>One of the dictionary definitions of the word investment is “Property or another possession acquired for future financial return or benefit”. The key word here being “future”. Often people are confused with the <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>holding period</a> for investment. While there are various <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>types of investments</a>, we are going to focus on long term financial <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>investment mistakes</a> to avoid. In a country like India the importance of investing is often misunderstood and hence people go on to make <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>investment decision </a>that are unwise and generally end up getting frustrated in the long run. There are people who gain half knowledge by reading a few snippets from various media and then take decisions of investments which often go awry.</p><p>While we will point out some of the common <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>investment mistakes</a> to avoid, we recommend that when in doubt it is always better to hire the services of a good <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>investment planner</a>. You need to identify an expert who has vast experience in the field of investing and one who has a proven track record as there are many fly by night operators who shut down eventually. So without further ado here are some of the common <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>investment mistakes</a> for you to avoid.</p><p><strong>Mistake number 1:</strong> Not starting saving for retirement early enough. I cannot stress the importance of this number one investment avenue. People who start early benefit hugely. The earlier you start the better it is as the <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>power of compounding</a> works in your favour. It is always a good idea to teach your children the <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>power of compounding </a>at an early age, so that when they start off their careers, they will invest from an early age. If you are one of those for whom age is not on your side, then one needs to look at equity based mutual funds to invest in. While the risk appetite is on the higher side, so are the returns. The high returns will offset some of the <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>financial benefits</a> that you may have lost with time.</p><p><strong>Mistake number 2:</strong> Not buying adequate <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>health insurance</a> and <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>term insurance</a>: Let’s face it; this is again one of the more ignored areas of investment. Most of us do not even consider it to be an investment. The thought process being why put money when nothing is going to happen to me and I am not going to get any financial returns on it in the long run. This thought process is flawed as a tragedy could befall anybody and at any time or any place. One should be prepared for the worst. Should a tragedy occur, and if you are disabled and unable to work, or in the event of your untimely death, your family will be left with no alternate source of income which they can survive on. Imagine if your monthly expenses are approximately 50 to 60 thousand rupees, where are you or your family going to get this income from? If you are in your thirties or forties, your life span will be there for another forty to fifty years and you will need income to survive. Hence it is advisable to have both medical and term life insurance as an investment, wherein you will get a substantial amount that will provide you with the necessary monthly outgo.</p><p><strong>Mistake number 3:</strong> Investing bulk of the money in <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>fixed deposits</a>. You may have the habit of investing your hard earned money in <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>fixed deposits</a>. While you are on the right track, the question to ask is, will the interest on <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>fixed deposits</a> beat the <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>rate of inflation</a>? Probably it may beat it by 1 % or so, but have you accounted for the taxes on fixed deposit. Most people forget the tax angle. <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>Fixed deposits</a> monies after taxes and after adjusting for inflation will definitely not give you the same buying power that you have today. While we do not advocate doing away with <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>fixed deposit</a>s entirely due to their safety benefit. We recommend that you do not park a bulk of your investments in <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>fixed deposits</a>. Instead you should distribute your monies in debt funds with short durations or in FMP (<a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>Fixed Maturity Plans</a>). For tax efficiency you should invest in <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>bond funds</a> as the earnings get the benefit of indexation and are also taxed at 20%.</p><p><strong>Mistake number 4:</strong> Overspending and accumulating too much debt. If you are used to leading a lavish life, then chances are that you have multiple credit cards and personal <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>loans</a> or home <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>loans</a>. <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>Credit card spending</a>’s as they say are never ending traps. Once you are sucked into the vortex, it is very difficult to get out. The interest rates that you end up paying on credit cards and other <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>loans</a> like personal <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>loans</a>; you can comfortable use those monies for long term investments. You will be amazed at the returns just the interest component can generate. The problem with credit spending is that you have committed to pay at a later date for material things that you have bought now. If you just think about, where the money to pay for it later is going to come from you will get the realization that you have to earn to pay the money and that too with an additional amount in the form of interest. You then need to keep on earning, leading to a life full of stress and worries.</p><p>These are some of the common mistakes that generally people make, there are others and one needs to engage the services of an expert to try and mitigate all the risks and pitfalls associated with investing. With that I hope you have started off on the road to make making wise long term <a href='http://pehlakadam.in/' target='_blank'>investment decisions.</a></p></div>",
